WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:05.820 --> 00:00:06.770
IAN NI-LEWIS: Hello, everyone.

00:00:06.770 --> 00:00:08.490
My name is Ian Ni-Lewis.

00:00:08.490 --> 00:00:09.550
RETO MEIER: And I'm
Reto Meier.

00:00:09.550 --> 00:00:12.360
And on today's "App Clinic,"
we'll be looking at apps

00:00:12.360 --> 00:00:14.864
people while they're
traveling.

00:00:14.864 --> 00:00:16.280
IAN NI-LEWIS: [COUGHS]

00:00:16.280 --> 00:00:17.950
That's an excellent idea.

00:00:17.950 --> 00:00:20.190
And I just swallowed coffee
down my lungs.

00:00:20.190 --> 00:00:21.620
Why don't you take
the next line.

00:00:21.620 --> 00:00:22.940
RETO MEIER: That is the
wrong place to be

00:00:22.940 --> 00:00:25.010
drinking your coffee.

00:00:25.010 --> 00:00:28.180
Gone are the days of badly
folded maps, guidebooks, and

00:00:28.180 --> 00:00:30.210
laminated holiday itineraries.

00:00:30.210 --> 00:00:31.860
Today you can keep everything
you need in the

00:00:31.860 --> 00:00:34.300
palm of your hand.

00:00:34.300 --> 00:00:34.850
IAN NI-LEWIS: That's right.

00:00:34.850 --> 00:00:37.480
No longer will you look like a
bumbling tourist standing on

00:00:37.480 --> 00:00:40.370
the corner of Oxford Street and
Charing Cross Road with

00:00:40.370 --> 00:00:43.000
your London street map
unfolded before you,

00:00:43.000 --> 00:00:45.975
fruitlessly trying to figure
out which direction is--

00:00:45.975 --> 00:00:47.600
you know, I never
even do that.

00:00:47.600 --> 00:00:48.180
RETO MEIER: No?

00:00:48.180 --> 00:00:49.410
What's your plan?

00:00:49.410 --> 00:00:52.250
IAN NI-LEWIS: My plan is,
I'm always looking

00:00:52.250 --> 00:00:53.190
at the curb in London.

00:00:53.190 --> 00:00:55.570
Because it tells me which way
the traffic is flowing.

00:00:55.570 --> 00:00:56.510
RETO MEIER: That is very true.

00:00:56.510 --> 00:00:58.410
Keeping your eye on the road
is probably wise for an

00:00:58.410 --> 00:00:59.830
American in London if
you don't want to be

00:00:59.830 --> 00:01:01.300
murdered by a black cab.

00:01:01.300 --> 00:01:02.800
IAN NI-LEWIS: In any case,
let's face it.

00:01:02.800 --> 00:01:06.290
When you're in a foreign city,
foreign country, there's a lot

00:01:06.290 --> 00:01:07.680
to keep in your mind.

00:01:07.680 --> 00:01:11.104
And I don't think my mind
is big enough to

00:01:11.104 --> 00:01:11.800
encompass it all.

00:01:11.800 --> 00:01:13.360
RETO MEIER: Well, you want to
be able to use your mind for

00:01:13.360 --> 00:01:16.030
things like appreciating the
sights and sounds of the new

00:01:16.030 --> 00:01:18.390
city that you're visiting, not
trying to remember exactly

00:01:18.390 --> 00:01:20.750
where you need to be and how
you're going to get there.

00:01:20.750 --> 00:01:22.070
IAN NI-LEWIS: And you certainly
do not want to be

00:01:22.070 --> 00:01:25.267
unfolding a paper map because
that's just like a sign that

00:01:25.267 --> 00:01:25.830
says "mug me."

00:01:25.830 --> 00:01:27.090
RETO MEIER: Yeah, please
steal my stuff.

00:01:27.090 --> 00:01:27.970
I have stuff.

00:01:27.970 --> 00:01:31.010
I probably have three weeks'
worth of money in my pocket.

00:01:31.010 --> 00:01:31.985
Please, rob me.

00:01:31.985 --> 00:01:33.780
And that is not the message you
want to be sending out.

00:01:33.780 --> 00:01:35.220
IAN NI-LEWIS: It's funny,
because you do get different

00:01:35.220 --> 00:01:36.480
reactions in every city.

00:01:36.480 --> 00:01:40.110
For instance, in London, I think
they just try and sell

00:01:40.110 --> 00:01:41.820
you a three-card Monte.

00:01:41.820 --> 00:01:43.800
In New York, they kill you.

00:01:43.800 --> 00:01:46.025
In Beijing, they want to
take you to tea, and

00:01:46.025 --> 00:01:47.760
then you pay for it.

00:01:47.760 --> 00:01:50.680
And in Shanghai, they want to
introduce you to your sister--

00:01:50.680 --> 00:01:52.030
their sister.

00:01:52.030 --> 00:01:53.780
RETO MEIER: Well, introducing
them to my sister would be

00:01:53.780 --> 00:01:54.350
interesting.

00:01:54.350 --> 00:01:54.840
IAN NI-LEWIS: Eh, that too.

00:01:54.840 --> 00:01:56.320
RETO MEIER: Particularly as
I don't have a sister.

00:01:56.320 --> 00:01:58.710
Anyway, so today we're going
to be looking at four apps

00:01:58.710 --> 00:02:02.820
that the viewers have nominated
as must-have travel

00:02:02.820 --> 00:02:04.990
assistance apps.

00:02:04.990 --> 00:02:07.870
So we're going to be looking
at social venue discovery

00:02:07.870 --> 00:02:09.330
classic Foursquare--

00:02:09.330 --> 00:02:10.949
IAN NI-LEWIS: The ultimate
in travel management--

00:02:10.949 --> 00:02:11.910
TripIt.

00:02:11.910 --> 00:02:14.550
RETO MEIER: --and one-click
location-sharing widget, Share

00:02:14.550 --> 00:02:15.960
Where location widget.

00:02:15.960 --> 00:02:17.320
IAN NI-LEWIS: Excellent.

00:02:17.320 --> 00:02:19.470
We'll be taking a closer look
at each of these apps and

00:02:19.470 --> 00:02:22.100
using them as a kicking off
point to explore the

00:02:22.100 --> 00:02:24.820
technologies and the best
practices that you need in

00:02:24.820 --> 00:02:28.550
order to create a must-have
travel app.

00:02:28.550 --> 00:02:31.680
RETO MEIER: All that
and more on--

00:02:31.680 --> 00:02:35.520
IAN NI-LEWIS: "The
App Clinic."

00:02:35.520 --> 00:02:37.380
RETO MEIER: So a travel
assistant is a pretty broad

00:02:37.380 --> 00:02:39.530
category, and that's being
reflected in the three apps

00:02:39.530 --> 00:02:41.580
that we'll be looking
at today.

00:02:41.580 --> 00:02:43.060
IAN NI-LEWIS: As part of the
Developer Relations team at

00:02:43.060 --> 00:02:46.320
Google, travel is a big part of
our job-- or it used to be

00:02:46.320 --> 00:02:50.830
before we got this boss video
studio, the video studio that

00:02:50.830 --> 00:02:52.140
puts that thing in back of us.

00:02:52.140 --> 00:02:54.720
Hey!

00:02:54.720 --> 00:02:57.460
So this is a category that we
are intimately familiar with.

00:02:57.460 --> 00:02:58.870
I've been traveling
for work for what?

00:02:58.870 --> 00:03:01.880
10 years now, and it
can be a nightmare.

00:03:01.880 --> 00:03:03.800
RETO MEIER: It's also one of
the more popular groups of

00:03:03.800 --> 00:03:05.060
apps in Google Play.

00:03:05.060 --> 00:03:07.380
And the popular apps in this
category tend to have very

00:03:07.380 --> 00:03:10.210
loyal and passionate uses.

00:03:10.210 --> 00:03:13.100
Take, for example, Foursquare.

00:03:15.600 --> 00:03:17.170
So let's have a look.

00:03:17.170 --> 00:03:18.450
Boy, look at that.

00:03:18.450 --> 00:03:20.090
IAN NI-LEWIS: Beautiful.

00:03:20.090 --> 00:03:25.660
Now this isn't a travel app per
se, but it's definitely

00:03:25.660 --> 00:03:27.060
useful as a travel app.

00:03:27.060 --> 00:03:29.540
I think you had some insights
into that recently.

00:03:29.540 --> 00:03:29.870
RETO MEIER: Absolutely.

00:03:29.870 --> 00:03:32.432
Let's see.

00:03:32.432 --> 00:03:34.330
We want to put that in front.

00:03:34.330 --> 00:03:37.350
In fact, yeah.

00:03:37.350 --> 00:03:38.910
I remember how this was
supposed to work now.

00:03:38.910 --> 00:03:39.340
IAN NI-LEWIS: Yes, indeed.

00:03:39.340 --> 00:03:41.660
RETO MEIER: Excellent.

00:03:41.660 --> 00:03:44.060
So when I was growing up in
Australia, Foursquare was the

00:03:44.060 --> 00:03:47.010
name of an independent group of
supermarkets whose TV ads

00:03:47.010 --> 00:03:50.170
implored me to come in
for a square deal.

00:03:50.170 --> 00:03:52.600
So every time I look at this
app, I hear the jingle playing

00:03:52.600 --> 00:03:53.700
in my head.

00:03:53.700 --> 00:03:58.150
Leaving that aside, I'm a big
fan of Foursquare, both for

00:03:58.150 --> 00:04:01.240
the service and the features
that they offer as well as

00:04:01.240 --> 00:04:03.880
their passion for creating a
really great user experience,

00:04:03.880 --> 00:04:05.560
which is a really
important thing.

00:04:05.560 --> 00:04:07.670
We can see that over the course
of the years, the

00:04:07.670 --> 00:04:09.820
Foursquare app has really
progressed.

00:04:09.820 --> 00:04:11.490
As each version of Android
has come out, they've

00:04:11.490 --> 00:04:12.510
refreshed the UI.

00:04:12.510 --> 00:04:14.610
They've taken advantage of some
of our best practices.

00:04:14.610 --> 00:04:17.589
So this is an app that I'm
a really big fan of.

00:04:17.589 --> 00:04:19.760
Now, strictly speaking, you
don't need to be traveling for

00:04:19.760 --> 00:04:22.000
Foursquare to be useful.

00:04:22.000 --> 00:04:23.970
In a lot of ways, it's most
useful when you're close to

00:04:23.970 --> 00:04:25.400
home, doing your
daily routine.

00:04:25.400 --> 00:04:28.740
I know a lot of people whose
coffee shop loyalty is based

00:04:28.740 --> 00:04:32.340
around fierce competition to
maintain their status as mayor

00:04:32.340 --> 00:04:34.600
of Pete's Coffee Shop on the
corner of El Camino and San

00:04:34.600 --> 00:04:35.980
Antonio roads.

00:04:35.980 --> 00:04:38.630
Now, a big part of Foursquare's
success is also

00:04:38.630 --> 00:04:41.990
around the social elements of
its use, as indicated by this

00:04:41.990 --> 00:04:43.150
screenshot.

00:04:43.150 --> 00:04:46.040
It's a way to share where you
are, let you know where your

00:04:46.040 --> 00:04:48.750
friends are hanging out, and
all those sorts of things.

00:04:48.750 --> 00:04:51.490
But for today, we're going to
be focusing on its use while

00:04:51.490 --> 00:04:52.690
you're on the road.

00:04:52.690 --> 00:04:54.670
And that's where I found it
to be the most compelling.

00:04:54.670 --> 00:04:57.540
When I'm away from home on a
trip, there's really no chance

00:04:57.540 --> 00:04:59.800
I'm going to become the mayor
of anything except for maybe

00:04:59.800 --> 00:05:01.170
the hotel that I'm saying at.

00:05:01.170 --> 00:05:04.700
So the app's primary use case
switches is from consistent

00:05:04.700 --> 00:05:07.505
use of the same venues to
discovery and exploration.

00:05:07.505 --> 00:05:09.210
IAN NI-LEWIS: Now, this is the
part that I really wanted to

00:05:09.210 --> 00:05:13.060
hear about because I have
avoided Foursquare forever.

00:05:13.060 --> 00:05:15.490
First, because it was a hipster
app, and second,

00:05:15.490 --> 00:05:19.510
because I just couldn't see
the use in being a mayor.

00:05:19.510 --> 00:05:22.060
I'm the kind of person who's
so ultra-competitive that I

00:05:22.060 --> 00:05:24.330
avoid competition just so
I don't have to lose.

00:05:24.330 --> 00:05:25.220
RETO MEIER: That's
pretty hard core.

00:05:25.220 --> 00:05:25.650
IAN NI-LEWIS: Yeah.

00:05:25.650 --> 00:05:27.840
RETO MEIER: I like it.

00:05:27.840 --> 00:05:30.690
So when I lived in London, I'd
visit the mother ship here at

00:05:30.690 --> 00:05:31.930
Google every three
months or so.

00:05:31.930 --> 00:05:34.390
And as soon as I landed in
SFO and checked in to the

00:05:34.390 --> 00:05:36.310
terminal, it was game on--

00:05:36.310 --> 00:05:38.730
coffee shops, hotels,
restaurants, hot dog stands,

00:05:38.730 --> 00:05:39.980
pretty much anything.

00:05:39.980 --> 00:05:41.290
I used to travel with--

00:05:41.290 --> 00:05:43.730
well, I think only once or twice
with Nick and Richard.

00:05:43.730 --> 00:05:46.230
And those guys would be on the
Cal train checking into each

00:05:46.230 --> 00:05:48.540
Cal train stop as they
went past it.

00:05:48.540 --> 00:05:50.750
So as far as competition
goes, those guys

00:05:50.750 --> 00:05:52.360
are pretty hard core.

00:05:52.360 --> 00:05:54.540
So the thrill of rocketing
up the leaderboard is a

00:05:54.540 --> 00:05:57.940
short-term gain, although what
really makes this app a travel

00:05:57.940 --> 00:06:01.040
assistance powerhouse is its
discoverability features.

00:06:01.040 --> 00:06:02.485
So back in--

00:06:02.485 --> 00:06:03.810
I can't even remember
when it was--

00:06:03.810 --> 00:06:08.140
2009, 2010, whenever the Nexus
One came out I went on a

00:06:08.140 --> 00:06:10.330
10-day European road show where
we hit something like

00:06:10.330 --> 00:06:14.050
nine cities in 10 days, stayed
in each one just long enough

00:06:14.050 --> 00:06:16.710
to get a good night's sleep,
hand out a couple Nexus Ones,

00:06:16.710 --> 00:06:18.000
and grab a meal.

00:06:18.000 --> 00:06:18.800
So suddenly--

00:06:18.800 --> 00:06:20.390
IAN NI-LEWIS: We don't do that
anymore, by the way.

00:06:20.390 --> 00:06:22.850
We do not hand out
phones anymore.

00:06:22.850 --> 00:06:23.650
RETO MEIER: Which is sad.

00:06:23.650 --> 00:06:24.480
That was a lot of fun.

00:06:24.480 --> 00:06:26.600
It was an easy way to make
friends in foreign cities.

00:06:26.600 --> 00:06:27.060
IAN NI-LEWIS: Right?

00:06:27.060 --> 00:06:29.550
It's like being those GIs in
World War II with their

00:06:29.550 --> 00:06:30.420
chocolate and cigarettes.

00:06:30.420 --> 00:06:30.880
RETO MEIER: Exactly.

00:06:30.880 --> 00:06:31.240
They loved me.

00:06:31.240 --> 00:06:33.220
Everywhere I went,
they loved me.

00:06:33.220 --> 00:06:35.460
I'm sure it had nothing to
do with the giveaways.

00:06:35.460 --> 00:06:37.750
So suddenly, having an app that
tells you where you can

00:06:37.750 --> 00:06:40.860
get a good meal and rewards you
with points for doing so

00:06:40.860 --> 00:06:42.910
really becomes very appealing.

00:06:42.910 --> 00:06:45.760
So I'm going to go into more
detail as to how the social

00:06:45.760 --> 00:06:48.370
discovery service on
Foursquare works a

00:06:48.370 --> 00:06:49.620
little later on.

00:06:49.620 --> 00:06:52.290
But first, let's take
a look at TripIt.

00:06:52.290 --> 00:06:54.860
IAN NI-LEWIS: Indeed.

00:06:54.860 --> 00:06:55.920
Oh wow.

00:06:55.920 --> 00:06:56.780
It's totally covered up.

00:06:56.780 --> 00:06:57.725
OK.

00:06:57.725 --> 00:06:58.450
Oh, right.

00:06:58.450 --> 00:06:59.360
We're supposed to
do it this way.

00:06:59.360 --> 00:07:00.960
RETO MEIER: Yeah, clever, huh?

00:07:00.960 --> 00:07:02.730
IAN NI-LEWIS: I love TripIt.

00:07:02.730 --> 00:07:04.980
By the way, I should
mention that Reto

00:07:04.980 --> 00:07:06.570
fracking loves TripIt.

00:07:06.570 --> 00:07:06.910
RETO MEIER: I do.

00:07:06.910 --> 00:07:09.160
I love it a lot.

00:07:09.160 --> 00:07:11.140
IAN NI-LEWIS: But I don't
fracking love it, because it's

00:07:11.140 --> 00:07:12.280
not 2008 anymore.

00:07:12.280 --> 00:07:12.760
RETO MEIER: Burn!

00:07:12.760 --> 00:07:14.620
IAN NI-LEWIS: When I started
going on business trips, I

00:07:14.620 --> 00:07:17.740
didn't even have a cell phone,
much less a smartphone.

00:07:17.740 --> 00:07:20.470
I had to manually create my
own version of TripIt with

00:07:20.470 --> 00:07:22.690
printouts of bookings, and
receipts, and flight

00:07:22.690 --> 00:07:24.920
itineraries, and maps
to my apartment,

00:07:24.920 --> 00:07:26.380
and maps to the train.

00:07:26.380 --> 00:07:29.600
And I kept doing
this for years.

00:07:29.600 --> 00:07:31.540
When I worked for Microsoft, I
tried to do it with a Windows

00:07:31.540 --> 00:07:32.400
mobile phone.

00:07:32.400 --> 00:07:34.400
That didn't work out so well.

00:07:34.400 --> 00:07:36.410
Nothing against--

00:07:36.410 --> 00:07:37.170
well, OK.

00:07:37.170 --> 00:07:41.150
Anyway, later on, I switched to
an iPhone, and then when I

00:07:41.150 --> 00:07:42.960
came here, I switched
to an Android phone.

00:07:42.960 --> 00:07:46.090
But honestly, the experience
was still unsatisfying.

00:07:46.090 --> 00:07:49.830
And the most important problem
was that my itineraries would

00:07:49.830 --> 00:07:51.360
be in my email.

00:07:51.360 --> 00:07:53.690
And I'd have to make sure, A,
that it was synced to the

00:07:53.690 --> 00:07:58.670
right folder in my email, and
B, that it synced and remain

00:07:58.670 --> 00:08:03.190
synced and didn't get tossed out
by the time I needed it.

00:08:03.190 --> 00:08:07.470
So I would frequently find
myself in line for, let's say,

00:08:07.470 --> 00:08:11.310
a rental car, frantically
charging my phone off of my

00:08:11.310 --> 00:08:16.000
laptop battery pack, just so I
could bring up an email that

00:08:16.000 --> 00:08:18.420
told me where and when
I was supposed to be

00:08:18.420 --> 00:08:20.250
at a certain place.

00:08:20.250 --> 00:08:23.260
At this point, though, I don't
have to do any of that.

00:08:23.260 --> 00:08:26.950
With TripIt, I can just set it
up to go through my email and

00:08:26.950 --> 00:08:31.490
find all of the travel-related
stuff, although it turns out

00:08:31.490 --> 00:08:33.559
that the security guys at
Google don't like that.

00:08:33.559 --> 00:08:34.830
So I had to stop that.

00:08:34.830 --> 00:08:36.799
But fortunately, what you can
do is set up an email

00:08:36.799 --> 00:08:38.130
forwarding rule.

00:08:38.130 --> 00:08:41.280
Just take everything that you
get from Expedia or Carlson

00:08:41.280 --> 00:08:45.100
Wagonlit or the other places
that we use to book travel and

00:08:45.100 --> 00:08:46.480
just forward it on to TripIt.

00:08:46.480 --> 00:08:48.460
And TripIt will actually
figure out

00:08:48.460 --> 00:08:50.850
what the email means.

00:08:50.850 --> 00:08:53.650
It'll pull out all of the
details about you hotel and

00:08:53.650 --> 00:08:55.290
about your flights.

00:08:55.290 --> 00:09:00.680
And then it will store that
and send you reminders

00:09:00.680 --> 00:09:02.690
whenever you need them.

00:09:02.690 --> 00:09:05.145
So by the time I'm sitting in
the taxi to go to the airport,

00:09:05.145 --> 00:09:08.190
I've got my entire trip right
in front of me-- hotels,

00:09:08.190 --> 00:09:13.540
weather, cars, directions, even
information about what

00:09:13.540 --> 00:09:15.480
friends of mine that use TripIt
are going to be in the

00:09:15.480 --> 00:09:17.120
same place at the same time.

00:09:17.120 --> 00:09:20.710
But for me, the most exciting
part about TripIt is just the

00:09:20.710 --> 00:09:22.470
way it seems to work
like magic.

00:09:22.470 --> 00:09:24.360
Everything just appears.

00:09:24.360 --> 00:09:25.790
It comes up when it should.

00:09:25.790 --> 00:09:28.680
It lets me know what time
I need to be where.

00:09:28.680 --> 00:09:31.630
It figures out where I am
and where I need to be.

00:09:31.630 --> 00:09:35.070
And it works offline without
having to connect up to an

00:09:35.070 --> 00:09:36.850
internet, which is really,
really important as you're

00:09:36.850 --> 00:09:40.300
traveling, because a lot of
times, internet access is

00:09:40.300 --> 00:09:43.600
either unavailable or incredibly
expensive.

00:09:43.600 --> 00:09:46.170
It also does some clever
things with intents.

00:09:46.170 --> 00:09:49.360
And Reto's going to be going
over that a little bit later.

00:09:49.360 --> 00:09:52.460
But before we do that, it's time
to take a quick look at--

00:09:55.260 --> 00:09:55.820
RETO MEIER: We're going
to take a look

00:09:55.820 --> 00:09:58.380
at Share Where widget.

00:09:58.380 --> 00:09:59.020
IAN NI-LEWIS: Nice handoff.

00:09:59.020 --> 00:09:59.670
