to be in frame.

00:10:03.800 --> 00:10:07.270
Now, I just want to take a
moment to comment on the

00:10:07.270 --> 00:10:10.580
Google Play landing page for
Share Where location widget.

00:10:10.580 --> 00:10:12.160
I really love the icon here.

00:10:12.160 --> 00:10:14.490
It's got that distinctive shape
that provides really

00:10:14.490 --> 00:10:17.640
strong branding and even a hint
as to what the app does

00:10:17.640 --> 00:10:21.050
without resorting to that square
with rounded corners

00:10:21.050 --> 00:10:21.530
that you see so much.

00:10:21.530 --> 00:10:22.230
IAN NI-LEWIS: Right.

00:10:22.230 --> 00:10:24.740
They have a great icon, and it
doesn't have a background.

00:10:24.740 --> 00:10:25.490
Love it.

00:10:25.490 --> 00:10:25.930
RETO MEIER: Exactly.

00:10:25.930 --> 00:10:28.560
It's also great to see that
they've got a feature graphic.

00:10:28.560 --> 00:10:31.260
But here I think they could
take another pass at this.

00:10:31.260 --> 00:10:32.950
The feature graphics are
really used in a lot of

00:10:32.950 --> 00:10:36.350
different places, including on
the phone, not always at this

00:10:36.350 --> 00:10:39.200
massive size and resolution
that you can see here.

00:10:39.200 --> 00:10:41.980
So a graphic like this that
includes a lot of text is

00:10:41.980 --> 00:10:44.240
going to be pretty illegible
when it gets shrunk down into

00:10:44.240 --> 00:10:45.160
the smaller sizes.

00:10:45.160 --> 00:10:48.250
So I'd suggest it you rely on
the description field, which

00:10:48.250 --> 00:10:51.140
is just below it, to detail the
functionality of the app,

00:10:51.140 --> 00:10:52.760
and really make the
feature graphic

00:10:52.760 --> 00:10:53.820
a little more stylized.

00:10:53.820 --> 00:10:57.270
In the same that you've got this
great logo icon, make it

00:10:57.270 --> 00:11:01.403
more like that so that you're
giving an idea of the app

00:11:01.403 --> 00:11:03.460
rather than trying to explain
everything within a small

00:11:03.460 --> 00:11:03.950
feature graphic.

00:11:03.950 --> 00:11:04.670
IAN NI-LEWIS: You know
what this feature

00:11:04.670 --> 00:11:05.680
graphic says to me?

00:11:05.680 --> 00:11:06.580
RETO MEIER: What does it say?

00:11:06.580 --> 00:11:09.440
IAN NI-LEWIS: It says, they
hired a great designer, and he

00:11:09.440 --> 00:11:10.990
made a great icon.

00:11:10.990 --> 00:11:14.790
And then the CEO put together
the feature graphic.

00:11:14.790 --> 00:11:16.170
RETO MEIER: We've got
everything we need.

00:11:16.170 --> 00:11:18.210
We don't need to pay another
guy a couple of grand to

00:11:18.210 --> 00:11:19.360
create the feature graphic.

00:11:19.360 --> 00:11:19.980
IAN NI-LEWIS: Exactly.

00:11:19.980 --> 00:11:21.040
I've got Photoshop.

00:11:21.040 --> 00:11:21.660
RETO MEIER: Exactly.

00:11:21.660 --> 00:11:24.580
So yeah, maybe make it look
like a designer did the

00:11:24.580 --> 00:11:25.650
feature graphic as well.

00:11:25.650 --> 00:11:27.270
I think that's really going
to help you out.

00:11:27.270 --> 00:11:30.490
It just gives you that much
more professional feel.

00:11:30.490 --> 00:11:33.270
And now if we actually look at
the app itself, in terms of

00:11:33.270 --> 00:11:36.090
functionality, this is
a much simpler--

00:11:36.090 --> 00:11:39.160
maybe you would even say tighter
focus than either of

00:11:39.160 --> 00:11:40.725
the other apps we're
looking at today.

00:11:40.725 --> 00:11:42.450
So the idea here is a
pretty simple one.

00:11:42.450 --> 00:11:44.710
It lets you create a home screen
widget or a number of

00:11:44.710 --> 00:11:48.340
home screen widgets which will
send preset messages to one or

00:11:48.340 --> 00:11:49.230
more recipients.

00:11:49.230 --> 00:11:52.090
And those messages can go out
via SMS, email, or actually

00:11:52.090 --> 00:11:54.750
using any app that you
like using intents.

00:11:54.750 --> 00:11:56.980
It's a simple concept, and one
which I actually considered

00:11:56.980 --> 00:12:01.760
writing a while back, an app I
called one-click SMS, which

00:12:01.760 --> 00:12:02.820
had a very similar idea.

00:12:02.820 --> 00:12:05.020
So if I just wanted to always
tell my wife I'm on my way

00:12:05.020 --> 00:12:07.760
home when I was on my way home
without having to try and do

00:12:07.760 --> 00:12:09.790
all the swipey stuff,
just press a button.

00:12:09.790 --> 00:12:12.020
And that's exactly what
this app does.

00:12:12.020 --> 00:12:14.870
So I love the idea of having a
one-touch emergency widget on

00:12:14.870 --> 00:12:18.640
my home screen to let friends
and family know that I've

00:12:18.640 --> 00:12:20.690
survived the inevitable
San Francisco

00:12:20.690 --> 00:12:24.300
earthquake, or that I'm--

00:12:24.300 --> 00:12:25.080
I'll try that again.

00:12:25.080 --> 00:12:26.120
And that I'm OK.

00:12:26.120 --> 00:12:30.080
Or that I'm not OK and having
my location embedded within

00:12:30.080 --> 00:12:32.070
that message so that they know
where in the rubble to dig

00:12:32.070 --> 00:12:34.880
through I think would be really
useful, as well as

00:12:34.880 --> 00:12:37.150
things like I've arrived safely,
my flight's just

00:12:37.150 --> 00:12:40.790
landed, I'm on my way home, any
of those sorts of things.

00:12:40.790 --> 00:12:42.740
So being able to do all of that
really quickly without

00:12:42.740 --> 00:12:45.630
having to scroll through
contacts lists or try and type

00:12:45.630 --> 00:12:49.050
in a keyboard while I'm walking,
half-asleep with jet

00:12:49.050 --> 00:12:51.340
lag, is really a plus.

00:12:51.340 --> 00:12:53.530
There's some UI work
that could be done

00:12:53.530 --> 00:12:54.460
to improve the UX.

00:12:54.460 --> 00:12:56.860
And I'll go into a little bit
more detail on that later.

00:12:56.860 --> 00:12:58.740
But they've done some great work
in terms of keeping the

00:12:58.740 --> 00:13:01.450
functionality simple and using
intents to make the app even

00:13:01.450 --> 00:13:04.270
powerful without having
to do much extra work.

00:13:04.270 --> 00:13:06.915
So the best thing that they've
done is keep it simple in an

00:13:06.915 --> 00:13:10.370
app that does one thing, and
it does it very well.

00:13:10.370 --> 00:13:11.840
IAN NI-LEWIS: Love it.

00:13:11.840 --> 00:13:14.570
So each of these apps offers
some valuable features to help

00:13:14.570 --> 00:13:16.500
you when you're traveling.

00:13:16.500 --> 00:13:19.040
Taking a step back, let's take
a look at the key features

00:13:19.040 --> 00:13:22.150
we're looking for in a pure
Android travel assistance app.

00:13:25.090 --> 00:13:28.190
RETO MEIER: OK, so the feature
set of each of these apps are

00:13:28.190 --> 00:13:29.000
kind of orthogonal.

00:13:29.000 --> 00:13:30.610
They're all really useful
for travelers.

00:13:30.610 --> 00:13:33.760
But there's very
little overlap.

00:13:33.760 --> 00:13:34.430
IAN NI-LEWIS: Right.

00:13:34.430 --> 00:13:38.170
So that's handy, because it
helps focus on how they're

00:13:38.170 --> 00:13:41.470
achieving some of that magical
feature set rather than

00:13:41.470 --> 00:13:43.420
debating the relative merits
of each feature.

00:13:43.420 --> 00:13:44.400
RETO MEIER: Exactly.

00:13:44.400 --> 00:13:48.610
So each of these apps needs to
work when I'm away from home,

00:13:48.610 --> 00:13:49.450
because they're travel apps.

00:13:49.450 --> 00:13:50.050
That's whole point.

00:13:50.050 --> 00:13:52.560
And so that means that I'm
likely to be charging my phone

00:13:52.560 --> 00:13:53.180
less often.

00:13:53.180 --> 00:13:55.410
So battery life and battery
consumption

00:13:55.410 --> 00:13:57.570
becomes really important.

00:13:57.570 --> 00:13:59.260
Data transfer is likely
to be slower.

00:13:59.260 --> 00:14:00.450
It's probably going
to be roaming.

00:14:00.450 --> 00:14:01.940
So it's probably going
to be expensive.

00:14:01.940 --> 00:14:03.400
So back home, I may not care.

00:14:03.400 --> 00:14:05.060
Suddenly, I'm in Italy.

00:14:05.060 --> 00:14:06.900
I'm paying a lot more for
my roaming costs.

00:14:06.900 --> 00:14:08.830
So I care about that
data transfer.

00:14:08.830 --> 00:14:10.550
And frankly, I'm probably going
to be turning it on and

00:14:10.550 --> 00:14:12.100
off, depending on when
I need stuff.

00:14:12.100 --> 00:14:14.190
IAN NI-LEWIS: At the same time,
a lot of times when

00:14:14.190 --> 00:14:17.950
you're traveling, you will get
great data every now and then,

00:14:17.950 --> 00:14:19.220
like when you've got Wi-Fi.

00:14:19.220 --> 00:14:19.760
RETO MEIER: Exactly.

00:14:19.760 --> 00:14:22.005
IAN NI-LEWIS: So in Italy, for
instance, they have Wi-Fi on

00:14:22.005 --> 00:14:22.550
the trains.

00:14:22.550 --> 00:14:23.060
If you can hook up to that--

00:14:23.060 --> 00:14:25.280
RETO MEIER: No, no-- they have
"wiffy" on the trains.

00:14:25.280 --> 00:14:26.200
IAN NI-LEWIS: Oh, I'm sorry.

00:14:26.200 --> 00:14:27.860
RETO MEIER: In Italy,
it's all "wiffy."

00:14:27.860 --> 00:14:29.320
IAN NI-LEWIS: Right.

00:14:29.320 --> 00:14:31.050
(AUSTRALIAN ACCENT) Shrimp
on the barbie.

00:14:31.050 --> 00:14:32.850
RETO MEIER: Exactly.

00:14:32.850 --> 00:14:35.450
IAN NI-LEWIS: Anyway, the point
is that you're not just

00:14:35.450 --> 00:14:38.040
having nonexistent data or
expensive data, you're having

00:14:38.040 --> 00:14:38.990
very intermittent data.

00:14:38.990 --> 00:14:43.490
So when you do have Wi-Fi, or
"wiffy," or "wah-foe," or

00:14:43.490 --> 00:14:47.190
whatever it is, you probably
want to take the most

00:14:47.190 --> 00:14:47.890
advantage of that.

00:14:47.890 --> 00:14:48.360
RETO MEIER: Exactly.

00:14:48.360 --> 00:14:50.420
And of course, location
is key.

00:14:50.420 --> 00:14:51.910
It's particularly important
because you want to

00:14:51.910 --> 00:14:52.870
know where you are.

00:14:52.870 --> 00:14:56.250
But this has to balanced around
the fact that you don't

00:14:56.250 --> 00:14:57.980
want to be draining the battery
getting those location

00:14:57.980 --> 00:14:58.830
updates all the time.

00:14:58.830 --> 00:15:02.080
So it's really a balancing act
of wanting to have fresh data,

00:15:02.080 --> 00:15:05.210
having constant data, working
offline, accurate location,

00:15:05.210 --> 00:15:07.640
without draining the battery
when, chances are, you're

00:15:07.640 --> 00:15:08.360
going to have your phone.

00:15:08.360 --> 00:15:09.880
You're going to be using it a
lot, but you're only going to

00:15:09.880 --> 00:15:11.260
be charging it at the
end of every day.

00:15:11.260 --> 00:15:12.440
IAN NI-LEWIS: Right.

00:15:12.440 --> 00:15:15.830
RETO MEIER: So the final result
really does emphasize

00:15:15.830 --> 00:15:21.140
the efficiency of apps
serving this market.

00:15:21.140 --> 00:15:23.100
IAN NI-LEWIS: So at last year's
I/O, Reto spent a bunch

00:15:23.100 --> 00:15:25.660
of time talking about how to
ensure your app is always

00:15:25.660 --> 00:15:28.630
fresh, which is extremely
important for apps.

00:15:28.630 --> 00:15:31.200
Is that an Android
using deodorant?

00:15:31.200 --> 00:15:33.680
RETO MEIER: It is, to
maintain freshness.

00:15:33.680 --> 00:15:34.220
IAN NI-LEWIS: Silly person.

00:15:34.220 --> 00:15:35.820
Androids don't smell.

00:15:35.820 --> 00:15:37.270
RETO MEIER: I'm just going to
put that in front so everyone

00:15:37.270 --> 00:15:40.510
can see the link to the
presentation as well.

00:15:40.510 --> 00:15:42.560
IAN NI-LEWIS: Indeed.

00:15:42.560 --> 00:15:44.660
RETO MEIER: Yeah, so it was all
about freshness, not just

00:15:44.660 --> 00:15:48.230
about Androids using deodorant,
but also--

00:15:48.230 --> 00:15:50.050
this is really important
for apps like

00:15:50.050 --> 00:15:52.420
Foursquare and TripIt.

00:15:52.420 --> 00:15:54.580
In these sorts of situations,
latency is your enemy,

00:15:54.580 --> 00:15:58.020
particularly if you're late for
a train, or you're just

00:15:58.020 --> 00:15:59.950
tired after a long day of
sightseeing, and you just want

00:15:59.950 --> 00:16:01.060
to find somewhere to eat.

00:16:01.060 --> 00:16:02.870
What you don't want to do is
spend a lot of time waiting

00:16:02.870 --> 00:16:05.640
for your phone to refresh, to
find a connection, to download

00:16:05.640 --> 00:16:05.895
information.

00:16:05.895 --> 00:16:08.200
You just want to have everything
at your fingertips

00:16:08.200 --> 00:16:11.270
so that you can glance at it and
keep running, basically.

00:16:15.250 --> 00:16:17.452
So Let's take a look
at Foursquare in

00:16:17.452 --> 00:16:20.830
a little more detail.

00:16:20.830 --> 00:16:24.280
All right, so let me bring
up the giant phone.

00:16:24.280 --> 00:16:27.580
IAN NI-LEWIS: Giant
fake phone, wooo!

00:16:27.580 --> 00:16:29.160
RETO MEIER: Perfect.

00:16:29.160 --> 00:16:33.090
So you can see that Foursquare
has done a fantastic job on

00:16:33.090 --> 00:16:34.100
pretty much everything.

00:16:34.100 --> 00:16:37.010
They've created something that's
really engaging, really

00:16:37.010 --> 00:16:38.330
interesting, really
great to look at.

00:16:38.330 --> 00:16:40.600
They've got a modern-looking
UI.

00:16:40.600 --> 00:16:42.022
You can look at it straightaway,
and you can see

00:16:42.022 --> 00:16:45.740
that it feels like a modern
Android phone.

00:16:45.740 --> 00:16:49.820
It's all using Holo theming,
all of that good stuff.

00:16:49.820 --> 00:16:53.220
And what's really useful here
is that what Ian is

00:16:53.220 --> 00:16:55.850
experimenting with here is the
local search feature, which we

00:16:55.850 --> 00:16:56.760
were discussing beforehand.

00:16:56.760 --> 00:16:58.710
And that's kind of
the key here.

00:16:58.710 --> 00:17:00.140
So you can see as we
go through here,

00:17:00.140 --> 00:17:00.765
it's got the map.

00:17:00.765 --> 00:17:02.580
It's showing where
your friends are.

00:17:02.580 --> 00:17:04.230
So if you're traveling in a
group, which is something we

00:17:04.230 --> 00:17:07.239
used to do a lot of for things
like Google Developer Days and

00:17:07.239 --> 00:17:09.609
DevFests, you can see where
other people that you're

00:17:09.609 --> 00:17:11.270
traveling with are at.

00:17:11.270 --> 00:17:13.930
Where's everyone going out for
a drink after the conference

00:17:13.930 --> 00:17:14.530
is finished?

00:17:14.530 --> 00:17:15.920
You can track them all down.

00:17:15.920 --> 00:17:18.150
You can find places that other
people have rated, perhaps on

00:17:18.150 --> 00:17:19.010
previous trips.

00:17:19.010 --> 00:17:22.099
So it's really a way for you to
be able to get some idea of

00:17:22.099 --> 00:17:25.060
confidence as to where
should I go?

00:17:25.060 --> 00:17:26.069
I just want to grab a meal.

00:17:26.069 --> 00:17:28.359
I'm in a place that I'm
not familiar with.

00:17:28.359 --> 00:17:29.520
What's a good place?

00:17:29.520 --> 00:17:32.290
Is there anywhere where it's
recommending in the nearby

00:17:32.290 --> 00:17:35.000
neighborhood that you would
agree or disagree with?

00:17:35.000 --> 00:17:36.500
IAN NI-LEWIS: Oh, absolutely,
Cafe Blaze.

00:17:36.500 --> 00:17:37.140
RETO MEIER: Blaze is great.

00:17:37.140 --> 00:17:38.770
IAN NI-LEWIS: Excellent cafe.

00:17:38.770 --> 00:17:41.770
RETO MEIER: So that's a good
choice that they've selected

00:17:41.770 --> 00:17:42.870
there, actually.

00:17:42.870 --> 00:17:45.450
And you can go through, and this
sort of consistent, clean

00:17:45.450 --> 00:17:48.360
UI is pervasive throughout
the entire app.

00:17:48.360 --> 00:17:49.920
It shows you the information
that you want--

00:17:49.920 --> 00:17:52.980
address, details, who's checked
in, photos, all of

00:17:52.980 --> 00:17:56.540
that sort of information, and
does it in a really clean,

00:17:56.540 --> 00:17:58.230
natural way.

00:17:58.230 --> 00:18:00.620
Again, what I really like about
this is the simplicity.

00:18:00.620 --> 00:18:03.060
It keeps everything
really simple.

00:18:03.060 --> 00:18:05.840
It shows you the information
that you need without making

00:18:05.840 --> 00:18:07.440
an overly complicated UI.

00:18:07.440 --> 00:18:10.610
So it really is something that's
easy to use and quite

00:18:10.610 --> 00:18:11.870
addictive, I think.

00:18:11.870 --> 00:18:13.900
You don't have this mountain
of information.

00:18:13.900 --> 00:18:16.715
I think that's a challenge for
a lot of apps like this is

00:18:16.715 --> 00:18:18.440
that there are a lot
of venues around.

00:18:18.440 --> 00:18:22.650
So there's this tendency to just
drop 1,000 pins on the

00:18:22.650 --> 00:18:23.870
screen at any given time.

00:18:23.870 --> 00:18:25.560
And that's not actually
really useful.

00:18:25.560 --> 00:18:28.010
What you want to know is,
where do I want to go?

00:18:28.010 --> 00:18:30.160
And this is somewhere where
choice can be a problem.

00:18:30.160 --> 00:18:32.670
If I'm standing on Castro
Street, I know there's a bunch

00:18:32.670 --> 00:18:34.250
of restaurants around.

00:18:34.250 --> 00:18:36.340
I want to know which one I
should go to based on the

00:18:36.340 --> 00:18:38.650
things that I like, that my
friends have checked in to,

00:18:38.650 --> 00:18:39.490
and those sorts of things.

00:18:39.490 --> 00:18:40.364
And that's something which
I think they do a

00:18:40.364 --> 00:18:41.410
really good job of.

00:18:41.410 --> 00:18:42.110
IAN NI-LEWIS: Absolutely.

00:18:42.110 --> 00:18:44.890
And just as a side note, you can
see that the design here

00:18:44.890 --> 00:18:45.660
is really beautiful.

00:18:45.660 --> 00:18:46.710
And they've done some
of the things that

00:18:46.710 --> 00:18:48.880
we've talked about--

00:18:48.880 --> 00:18:52.550
putting your media front and
center, making sure that you

00:18:52.550 --> 00:18:53.970
make good use of space.

00:18:53.970 --> 00:18:58.870
Every time something is blank,
it's for a reason, but mostly,

00:18:58.870 --> 00:19:01.510
just bringing up these
beautiful, beautiful pictures.

00:19:01.510 --> 00:19:01.990
RETO MEIER: Absolutely.

00:19:01.990 --> 00:19:03.240
I mean, that's what
this is all about.

00:19:03.240 --> 00:19:06.500
I mean, what Foursquare has ,
which a lot of other apps

00:19:06.500 --> 00:19:08.600
which are offering similar
services don't, is a huge

00:19:08.600 --> 00:19:11.710
community of people which
are contributing to the

00:19:11.710 --> 00:19:12.500
information here.

00:19:12.500 --> 00:19:15.210
So we have lots of pictures
contributed by users which you

00:19:15.210 --> 00:19:18.070
can trust, because it's not the
picture that the owner has

00:19:18.070 --> 00:19:21.360
taken on the day where he's
cleared out everyone and given

00:19:21.360 --> 00:19:22.800
everything a spic-and-span
clean.

00:19:22.800 --> 00:19:24.720
It's pictures which people have
taken while they've been

00:19:24.720 --> 00:19:25.820
hanging out there.

00:19:25.820 --> 00:19:27.860
So they've done a
really good job.

