So what I want to talk about a
little bit is use this as an

00:19:30.790 --> 00:19:35.810
excuse to talk a little bit
about how Foursquare have done

00:19:35.810 --> 00:19:38.260
the job that they have done.

00:19:38.260 --> 00:19:42.870
It's simple enough to get
location updates for Android.

00:19:42.870 --> 00:19:45.950
But what Foursquare have done a
really good job of is making

00:19:45.950 --> 00:19:48.920
sure that location updates are
as low latency as possible.

00:19:48.920 --> 00:19:50.930
So there's a few tricks you
can use to maintain your

00:19:50.930 --> 00:19:54.110
location freshness without
draining the battery

00:19:54.110 --> 00:19:55.140
completely.

00:19:55.140 --> 00:19:57.200
So you can significantly
reduce the battery--

00:19:57.200 --> 00:19:59.760
sorry, you can significantly
reduce the latency for getting

00:19:59.760 --> 00:20:02.860
your first location fix by
retrieving the last known

00:20:02.860 --> 00:20:05.220
location from the location
manager each

00:20:05.220 --> 00:20:07.360
time the app is resumed.

00:20:07.360 --> 00:20:09.020
So if you have a look at
this code snippet--

00:20:09.020 --> 00:20:11.980
I'll just pop that in front as
well so you can perhaps read

00:20:11.980 --> 00:20:14.300
that a little bit more easily.

00:20:14.300 --> 00:20:16.870
So in this snippet, we're going
to iterate through each

00:20:16.870 --> 00:20:19.580
location provider on the device,
including those that

00:20:19.580 --> 00:20:21.100
aren't currently available.

00:20:21.100 --> 00:20:24.320
And we're going to seek out
the most timely and most

00:20:24.320 --> 00:20:26.320
accurate last known location.

00:20:26.320 --> 00:20:29.210
So if there's one or more
locations available from

00:20:29.210 --> 00:20:31.900
within the allowed time frame,
then we can return the one

00:20:31.900 --> 00:20:33.470
which has the most
accurate result.

00:20:33.470 --> 00:20:35.060
And if there isn't,
then we return

00:20:35.060 --> 00:20:36.580
the most recent results.

00:20:36.580 --> 00:20:38.850
Though if we're just doing
that-- the most recent result,

00:20:38.850 --> 00:20:40.760
but it's kind of beyond
our latency window--

00:20:40.760 --> 00:20:43.300
it's pretty good practice to
request a single location

00:20:43.300 --> 00:20:47.130
update from every available
provider to try and get a more

00:20:47.130 --> 00:20:48.050
recent result.

00:20:48.050 --> 00:20:50.950
At this point, it doesn't even
matter which is the more

00:20:50.950 --> 00:20:51.670
accurate result.

00:20:51.670 --> 00:20:54.850
You just want to get something
that's a little more timely so

00:20:54.850 --> 00:20:56.620
that you get something
which is in the

00:20:56.620 --> 00:20:58.100
vaguely correct location.

00:20:58.100 --> 00:20:59.940
And then obviously, you can
continue to do your location

00:20:59.940 --> 00:21:03.540
updates to try and get something
even more useful.

00:21:03.540 --> 00:21:04.780
IAN NI-LEWIS: So one thing that
I've always wanted to ask

00:21:04.780 --> 00:21:06.565
you, Reto, about location,
because I know you're kind of

00:21:06.565 --> 00:21:07.500
the location guy.

00:21:07.500 --> 00:21:08.010
RETO MEIER: Sure.

00:21:08.010 --> 00:21:10.250
IAN NI-LEWIS: So I remember
when I first started

00:21:10.250 --> 00:21:12.450
traveling, and this was way back
in the Dark Ages when we

00:21:12.450 --> 00:21:15.830
didn't have offline maps and
we didn't have really good

00:21:15.830 --> 00:21:16.700
location providers.

00:21:16.700 --> 00:21:20.080
And I found out an app called
Maverick that was mostly for

00:21:20.080 --> 00:21:22.520
geocaching.

00:21:22.520 --> 00:21:25.670
And so they made it work
in the wilderness.

00:21:25.670 --> 00:21:26.070
RETO MEIER: Nice.

00:21:26.070 --> 00:21:28.100
IAN NI-LEWIS: And it turned
out that for me, anyway,

00:21:28.100 --> 00:21:30.850
coming from the US, London
was the wilderness.

00:21:30.850 --> 00:21:31.550
RETO MEIER: Effectively.

00:21:31.550 --> 00:21:34.960
IAN NI-LEWIS: So what it did was
it allowed me to download

00:21:34.960 --> 00:21:36.800
a bunch of map tiles,
which may or may not

00:21:36.800 --> 00:21:38.280
actually been legal.

00:21:38.280 --> 00:21:39.630
RETO MEIER: It downloaded
them regardless.

00:21:39.630 --> 00:21:40.720
IAN NI-LEWIS: Indeed.

00:21:40.720 --> 00:21:45.850
And then it would find GPS, but
it also kept track of my

00:21:45.850 --> 00:21:49.370
location through
dead reckoning.

00:21:49.370 --> 00:21:52.660
Do any of the phones we have
now do that automatically?

00:21:52.660 --> 00:21:54.450
Is that part of the
location provider?

00:21:54.450 --> 00:21:55.400
RETO MEIER: Not that
I'm aware of, no.

00:21:55.400 --> 00:21:58.300
I think the location providers
that we're using at the moment

00:21:58.300 --> 00:22:00.400
are fairly simplistic
in that it's just

00:22:00.400 --> 00:22:03.225
GPS or network location--

00:22:03.225 --> 00:22:03.870
what do we call it?

00:22:03.870 --> 00:22:07.870
NLP, Network Location
Provider.

00:22:07.870 --> 00:22:11.910
So using cell ID and Wi-Fi
rather than momentum and dead

00:22:11.910 --> 00:22:14.140
reckoning and those sorts of
things, although I think

00:22:14.140 --> 00:22:16.250
that's something which the
industry is heading towards.

00:22:16.250 --> 00:22:16.800
IAN NI-LEWIS: Right.

00:22:16.800 --> 00:22:18.530
RETO MEIER: So it would be
fantastic to see more and more

00:22:18.530 --> 00:22:21.930
of those sorts of features
become part of the location

00:22:21.930 --> 00:22:23.010
providers available.

00:22:23.010 --> 00:22:24.560
IAN NI-LEWIS: Wouldn't
that be great?

00:22:24.560 --> 00:22:27.670
Now, what implications does that
have for power, though?

00:22:27.670 --> 00:22:29.430
RETO MEIER: Well, I guess that's
kind of the question.

00:22:29.430 --> 00:22:31.980
And that's one of the important
reasons why within

00:22:31.980 --> 00:22:34.290
Android, you shouldn't be
specifying a particular

00:22:34.290 --> 00:22:35.300
location provider.

00:22:35.300 --> 00:22:38.110
So at the moment, it's just
assumed that GPS is going to

00:22:38.110 --> 00:22:40.530
drain your battery, and the
network location provider is

00:22:40.530 --> 00:22:42.950
going to be relatively
low-power.

00:22:42.950 --> 00:22:46.070
But these days, it's actually
becoming a point where a lot

00:22:46.070 --> 00:22:48.450
of the GPS chips are becoming
more and more power efficient

00:22:48.450 --> 00:22:51.790
and getting built into the
hardware itself so that the

00:22:51.790 --> 00:22:54.260
actual location drain is
significantly lower.

00:22:54.260 --> 00:22:57.310
By comparison, the network
location providers are using a

00:22:57.310 --> 00:23:01.100
lot more features, things like
gyroscopes, things like

00:23:01.100 --> 00:23:04.720
momentum, all of those things
which can comparatively

00:23:04.720 --> 00:23:06.730
increase its battery drain.

00:23:06.730 --> 00:23:09.140
So what it then means is it's
kind of up to the system to

00:23:09.140 --> 00:23:12.430
figure out how to balance those
things and provide you

00:23:12.430 --> 00:23:14.800
with as accurate a result
as you can without

00:23:14.800 --> 00:23:15.570
draining the battery.

00:23:15.570 --> 00:23:18.380
And so for us right now, that
means using things like

00:23:18.380 --> 00:23:22.700
criteria to specify a location
provider based on the power

00:23:22.700 --> 00:23:26.240
drain or the accuracy you need
rather than saying, hey, I

00:23:26.240 --> 00:23:28.410
think that this implies that,
so I'm going to use that

00:23:28.410 --> 00:23:30.040
particular provider.

00:23:30.040 --> 00:23:32.570
IAN NI-LEWIS: So as with many
things Android, you really

00:23:32.570 --> 00:23:36.540
don't want to go too low-level
yourself, because you know

00:23:36.540 --> 00:23:37.790
that things are going
to get better.

00:23:37.790 --> 00:23:40.000
And they're going to get better
in a very unpredictable

00:23:40.000 --> 00:23:42.860
way, where on some devices
they're much better in terms

00:23:42.860 --> 00:23:44.230
of power, for instance.

00:23:44.230 --> 00:23:47.190
And other devices, they haven't
made those changes.

00:23:47.190 --> 00:23:51.040
So you're always safest going
with the basic system.

00:23:51.040 --> 00:23:54.910
And then if you absolutely
have to tweak things for

00:23:54.910 --> 00:23:57.160
specific classes of devices,
maybe you want to do that.

00:23:57.160 --> 00:23:57.830
RETO MEIER: Exactly.

00:23:57.830 --> 00:24:00.500
A good example is if you're
creating a device which lets

00:24:00.500 --> 00:24:03.520
you understand how many GPS
satellites you've got in

00:24:03.520 --> 00:24:05.340
view-- and we looked at a couple
of these apps a little

00:24:05.340 --> 00:24:07.210
while ago, some of
these GPS apps.

00:24:07.210 --> 00:24:09.310
Clearly they want the GPS
provider, whether it's

00:24:09.310 --> 00:24:11.335
accurate or draining the battery
or whatever, they

00:24:11.335 --> 00:24:12.010
don't really care.

00:24:12.010 --> 00:24:13.140
That's not the point.

00:24:13.140 --> 00:24:14.290
For everything else,
you want to be as

00:24:14.290 --> 00:24:15.400
high-level as possible.

00:24:15.400 --> 00:24:17.790
And then trust that as the
framework team are able to

00:24:17.790 --> 00:24:20.360
make improvements to these APIs,
that suddenly your app

00:24:20.360 --> 00:24:22.280
will get better and more
efficient and more accurate

00:24:22.280 --> 00:24:23.520
without you actually having
to do anything.

00:24:23.520 --> 00:24:24.130
IAN NI-LEWIS: Right.

00:24:24.130 --> 00:24:25.830
Yeah, I think this
is a good area.

00:24:25.830 --> 00:24:29.020
If you're doing a location app,
stay tuned and make sure

00:24:29.020 --> 00:24:32.220
you follow not only Android,
but the different chipset

00:24:32.220 --> 00:24:34.730
vendors and see what kind of
changes they're making,

00:24:34.730 --> 00:24:36.220
because I know there's
a lot of active

00:24:36.220 --> 00:24:37.280
research in this area.

00:24:37.280 --> 00:24:37.500
RETO MEIER: Absolutely.

00:24:37.500 --> 00:24:40.430
I think we've been hearing a lot
about things like passive

00:24:40.430 --> 00:24:41.650
background location updates.

00:24:41.650 --> 00:24:45.310
And you can see apps like Google
Now, in fact, being

00:24:45.310 --> 00:24:48.190
able to give you these really
cool hints about how far

00:24:48.190 --> 00:24:53.710
you've walked or suggesting
things based on your location

00:24:53.710 --> 00:24:54.460
and those sorts of stuff.

00:24:54.460 --> 00:24:55.320
So that's kind of cool.

00:24:55.320 --> 00:24:57.080
I'm going to talk a little bit
about how you can do some of

00:24:57.080 --> 00:24:58.790
those things in just a minute.

00:24:58.790 --> 00:24:59.160
IAN NI-LEWIS: Great.

00:24:59.160 --> 00:24:59.530
Let's do that.

00:24:59.530 --> 00:25:01.960
RETO MEIER: So generally, I
prefer to use pending intents

00:25:01.960 --> 00:25:04.160
rather than location
listeners when I'm

00:25:04.160 --> 00:25:05.410
making my location requests.

00:25:05.410 --> 00:25:07.560
And that's because it offers the
flexibility of registering

00:25:07.560 --> 00:25:10.420
receivers in multiple activities
or services or even

00:25:10.420 --> 00:25:12.240
directly in a manifest.

00:25:12.240 --> 00:25:14.910
In fact, by doing that, you
can make your app silently

00:25:14.910 --> 00:25:17.040
update your location, just like
what we mentioned, and

00:25:17.040 --> 00:25:19.700
potentially even update the
list of nearby venues.

00:25:19.700 --> 00:25:22.950
So an app like Foursquare can
passively listen for these

00:25:22.950 --> 00:25:26.270
location changes, and then in
the background every once in a

00:25:26.270 --> 00:25:28.660
while actually pull down
nearby locations.

00:25:28.660 --> 00:25:31.680
So when you open the app, you're
not waiting for that

00:25:31.680 --> 00:25:33.770
feeling like it's
interminable.

00:25:33.770 --> 00:25:34.440
Come on.

00:25:34.440 --> 00:25:35.955
Yeah, I was there half
an hour ago.

00:25:35.955 --> 00:25:36.960
I'm here now.

00:25:36.960 --> 00:25:39.910
Just give me something
more reasonable.

00:25:39.910 --> 00:25:41.280
IAN NI-LEWIS: And let's
remember, too, that while

00:25:41.280 --> 00:25:44.010
you're doing this, it's very,
very important to persist that

00:25:44.010 --> 00:25:44.600
information.

00:25:44.600 --> 00:25:49.210
Because you're pending intents
and any listener of this type

00:25:49.210 --> 00:25:51.450
is going to be running in the
background, which means that

00:25:51.450 --> 00:25:54.730
if the user, let's say, boots up
a game or starts to run out

00:25:54.730 --> 00:25:57.230
of battery, you're going to be
on the list to be killed.

00:25:57.230 --> 00:26:00.940
And if you're keeping that
information in memory, then

00:26:00.940 --> 00:26:01.800
it's just going to go away.

00:26:01.800 --> 00:26:03.200
And essentially, you've
just wasted a bunch

00:26:03.200 --> 00:26:04.040
of power for nothing.

00:26:04.040 --> 00:26:06.940
So make absolutely sure that
that gets persisted out to

00:26:06.940 --> 00:26:10.140
either a content provider or
your own file system database

00:26:10.140 --> 00:26:11.220
or whatever.

00:26:11.220 --> 00:26:12.040
RETO MEIER: Share preferences
can be a good

00:26:12.040 --> 00:26:12.490
one for that as well.

00:26:12.490 --> 00:26:15.330
IAN NI-LEWIS: There
you go, exactly.

00:26:15.330 --> 00:26:15.730
RETO MEIER: Exactly.

00:26:15.730 --> 00:26:19.425
So now requesting locations
updates, particularly if

00:26:19.425 --> 00:26:21.610
you're using something like GPS,
anything which is high

00:26:21.610 --> 00:26:23.970
power while your app isn't
in the foreground, is

00:26:23.970 --> 00:26:25.000
kind of a bad idea.

00:26:25.000 --> 00:26:25.940
It's going to drain
the battery.

00:26:25.940 --> 00:26:28.240
It's going to make
people angry.

00:26:28.240 --> 00:26:30.440
So what you're going to do
instead is use a passive

00:26:30.440 --> 00:26:33.680
location provider to piggyback
your location updates when

00:26:33.680 --> 00:26:35.820
other apps are requesting
them.

00:26:35.820 --> 00:26:38.780
So again, I'm going to pop
the code in front.

00:26:38.780 --> 00:26:41.310
So you can see in this code
snippet, we request location

00:26:41.310 --> 00:26:43.850
updates using a passive
provider, this thing in a

00:26:43.850 --> 00:26:46.590
broadcast, of pending intent
whenever it receives any of

00:26:46.590 --> 00:26:48.030
those changes.

00:26:48.030 --> 00:26:50.940
And it includes a receiver
definition as well down at the

00:26:50.940 --> 00:26:54.160
bottom, which is what you put
in your manifest, which is

00:26:54.160 --> 00:26:57.560
then going to listen for those
broadcast intents in order so

00:26:57.560 --> 00:26:59.630
that you can then do something
with them.

00:26:59.630 --> 00:27:02.060
So within our receiver
definition, we can choose what

00:27:02.060 --> 00:27:04.565
to do when those new locations
coming in, which may be store

00:27:04.565 --> 00:27:07.440
the location for later use,
though often, that's going to

00:27:07.440 --> 00:27:10.050
be duplicating the work that
you can do just by querying

00:27:10.050 --> 00:27:12.580
the get last known location.

00:27:12.580 --> 00:27:14.710
Or you can do other things
like pre-fetching nearby

00:27:14.710 --> 00:27:16.700
locations when certain
conditions are met.

00:27:16.700 --> 00:27:18.890
So you may want to do that much
less frequently than the

00:27:18.890 --> 00:27:20.830
updates that you
are receiving.

00:27:20.830 --> 00:27:22.100
IAN NI-LEWIS: Exactly.

00:27:22.100 --> 00:27:24.375
Now, the door has just opened,
and Billy is sticking is head

00:27:24.375 --> 00:27:25.890
in, so there's something
wrong with the show.

00:27:25.890 --> 00:27:27.550
What's wrong, Billy?

00:27:27.550 --> 00:27:27.870
No?

00:27:27.870 --> 00:27:29.226
BILLY: All good.

00:27:29.226 --> 00:27:29.680
IAN NI-LEWIS: Oh.

00:27:29.680 --> 00:27:30.310
RETO MEIER: Outstanding.

00:27:30.310 --> 00:27:30.810
IAN NI-LEWIS: Beautiful.

00:27:30.810 --> 00:27:31.980
RETO MEIER: He's just
making sure we're

00:27:31.980 --> 00:27:32.900
actually doing work.

00:27:32.900 --> 00:27:34.380
We're not just sitting
in here drinking.

00:27:34.380 --> 00:27:35.440
IAN NI-LEWIS: Exactly.

00:27:35.440 --> 00:27:39.000
RETO MEIER: I respect his
confidence in us.

00:27:39.000 --> 00:27:41.320
IAN NI-LEWIS: Absolutely.

00:27:41.320 --> 00:27:43.630
RETO MEIER: Let's move on.

00:27:43.630 --> 00:27:47.820
That's an entirely blank screen,
very disconcerting.

00:27:47.820 --> 00:27:49.100
IAN NI-LEWIS: Mike Winton,
don't ever stick

00:27:49.100 --> 00:27:49.890
your head in again.

00:27:49.890 --> 00:27:53.430
You screwed up everything.

00:27:53.430 --> 00:27:55.370
RETO MEIER: So this technique
of pre-fetching

00:27:55.370 --> 00:27:56.670
can be really powerful.

00:27:56.670 --> 00:27:59.300
But it's also inherently risky,
as you're introducing

00:27:59.300 --> 00:28:02.410
battery and bandwidth cost by
downloading data that may

00:28:02.410 --> 00:28:03.670
never actually be necessary.

00:28:03.670 --> 00:28:06.590
So if you're looking at a travel
assistance app, that

00:28:06.590 --> 00:28:07.890
can be kind of touch and go.

00:28:07.890 --> 00:28:09.310
And that's something which
I think Foursquare are

00:28:09.310 --> 00:28:11.460
really aware of.

00:28:11.460 --> 00:28:15.040
And this is an app, where again,
that balance between

00:28:15.040 --> 00:28:17.440
being an app that you use a lot
at home and an app that's

00:28:17.440 --> 00:28:20.240
really useful when you're away
becomes an interesting balance

00:28:20.240 --> 00:28:22.750
of how do you maintain that
freshness without draining the

00:28:22.750 --> 00:28:25.070
battery and becoming something
which people don't want to

00:28:25.070 --> 00:28:26.700
have running when they're
overseas.

00:28:26.700 --> 00:28:28.440
IAN NI-LEWIS: Well, I think this
actually starts to get

00:28:28.440 --> 00:28:33.950
into the secret sauce of what
makes an app truly amazing and

00:28:33.950 --> 00:28:34.930
what it means--

00:28:34.930 --> 00:28:36.460
for instance, we've talked
about this with the video

00:28:36.460 --> 00:28:40.500
apps, where everybody and their
brother uses some form

00:28:40.500 --> 00:28:46.590
of media player on any platform,
Flash player on the

00:28:46.590 --> 00:28:47.780
web, for instance.

00:28:47.780 --> 00:28:49.820
But where the secret sauce comes
in is how do you make

00:28:49.820 --> 00:28:53.720
something start really fast and
play at a good bandwidth

00:28:53.720 --> 00:28:55.420
and switch bandwidth easily.

00:28:55.420 --> 00:28:59.040
And in location apps, it's
really, how do you know when a

00:28:59.040 --> 00:29:00.460
person's going to
try and use it?

00:29:00.460 --> 00:29:03.210
If you look at what we've done
with Google Now, it really

00:29:03.210 --> 00:29:06.340
tries to predict based on your
past behavior, what you're

00:29:06.340 --> 00:29:08.510
going to need at a
particular point.

00:29:08.510 --> 00:29:10.820
And I think that when you look
at Foursquare, you're seeing

00:29:10.820 --> 00:29:12.750
some of the smarts and some
of those intelligences.

00:29:12.750 --> 00:29:15.970
You could probably even go
further and make it into

00:29:15.970 --> 00:29:18.240
something where you kind
of know when the

00:29:18.240 --> 00:29:19.160
app's going to be needed.

00:29:19.160 --> 00:29:23.830
Because you can see where the
user is, and even how fast

00:29:23.830 --> 00:29:27.890
they're going and what time of
day it is, and predict what

00:29:27.890 --> 00:29:29.260
kind of information they're
going to need.

00:29:29.260 --> 00:29:30.440
RETO MEIER: Absolutely.

00:29:30.440 --> 00:29:33.450
So another useful best practice
is monitoring the

00:29:33.450 --> 00:29:35.010
state of your providers.

00:29:35.010 --> 00:29:36.400
So this is kind of important.

00:29:36.400 --> 00:29:38.910
When you make a location update
request, even when

00:29:38.910 --> 00:29:41.320
you're using criteria, the
location manager is just going

00:29:41.320 --> 00:29:44.390
to choose one of those providers
whose updates it's

00:29:44.390 --> 00:29:45.050
going to monitor.

00:29:45.050 --> 00:29:48.730
So whatever provider happens to
be active, whether the user

00:29:48.730 --> 00:29:53.170
has GPS ticked or the network
location provided ticked, it's

00:29:53.170 --> 00:29:54.500
going to try make
a determination

00:29:54.500 --> 00:29:55.380
based on what's available.

00:29:55.380 --> 00:29:57.600
But that can change
in real time.

00:29:57.600 --> 00:29:59.820
So again, I'm going to
stick this code--

00:29:59.820 --> 00:30:01.790
yeah, I'm going to stick
this in front.

00:30:01.790 --> 00:30:05.100
Then I can move around
a little bit more.

00:30:05.100 --> 00:30:07.100
So this snippet is monitoring
two conditions.

00:30:07.100 --> 00:30:09.690
It's checking to find out the
location provider that we're

00:30:09.690 --> 00:30:12.170
using to see if it's
being deactivated.

00:30:12.170 --> 00:30:13.720
So a user can turn
these on and off.

00:30:13.720 --> 00:30:16.210
So it's checking to make sure
that, OK, we've decided to use

00:30:16.210 --> 00:30:19.880
GPS, and the user goes
and turns off GPS.

00:30:19.880 --> 00:30:23.410
We're going to be able to then
find another provider.

00:30:23.410 --> 00:30:25.340
And likewise, we're going to
check to see if there is

00:30:25.340 --> 00:30:26.930
another provider that
becomes available.

00:30:26.930 --> 00:30:29.260
So maybe we would have used GPS,
but it was disabled, and

00:30:29.260 --> 00:30:30.090
then it gets turned on.

00:30:30.090 --> 00:30:32.720
We want to switch without the
user having to exit the app

00:30:32.720 --> 00:30:35.690
and come back in or manually
do something that way.

00:30:35.690 --> 00:30:37.880
It should all happen
dynamically.

00:30:37.880 --> 00:30:39.630
In either case, we're just going
to re-run the process

00:30:39.630 --> 00:30:43.270
used to determine which provider
that is currently

00:30:43.270 --> 00:30:46.490
available is best for
our current needs.

00:30:46.490 --> 00:30:48.390
And this technique ensures
that we can continue to

00:30:48.390 --> 00:30:51.400
receive location updates without
interruption even if

00:30:51.400 --> 00:30:53.440
the user is totaling
GPS and network

00:30:53.440 --> 00:30:54.690
location provider details.

