00:35:49.290 --> 00:35:51.730
And he's only been a little
bit bitter about it.

00:35:51.730 --> 00:35:54.400
RETO MEIER: Only a little.

00:35:54.400 --> 00:35:56.810
So even if you're not
downloading anything every

00:35:56.810 --> 00:35:58.740
time you do the poll, you're
still potentially

00:35:58.740 --> 00:36:00.000
draining the battery.

00:36:00.000 --> 00:36:03.750
And that's because of the way
that the battery life cycle

00:36:03.750 --> 00:36:07.050
model works-- or I should say
the cell network life cycle.

00:36:07.050 --> 00:36:09.750
Or the cell radio, which is
going to say on high power for

00:36:09.750 --> 00:36:13.600
around 10 seconds and around low
power for up to a minute

00:36:13.600 --> 00:36:14.950
every time you ping a server.

00:36:14.950 --> 00:36:18.150
Even if the server is
going, it's cool,

00:36:18.150 --> 00:36:18.860
nothing you need to do.

00:36:18.860 --> 00:36:20.740
It's still going to
drain the battery.

00:36:20.740 --> 00:36:23.620
So if you're doing these updates
every minute, then

00:36:23.620 --> 00:36:25.480
you're just leaving the cell
radio on permanently, which is

00:36:25.480 --> 00:36:27.620
going to destroy your
battery life.

00:36:27.620 --> 00:36:29.960
And so this is compounded by
the typical update rates of

00:36:29.960 --> 00:36:32.780
apps like TripIt, where if my
itinerary changes, I want that

00:36:32.780 --> 00:36:36.290
update, like, now, like
as soon as it happens.

00:36:36.290 --> 00:36:38.100
But it's not going to
happen that often.

00:36:38.100 --> 00:36:41.390
So how can we optimize
those updates and

00:36:41.390 --> 00:36:43.920
minimize the latency?

00:36:43.920 --> 00:36:44.930
Well, in fact--

00:36:44.930 --> 00:36:47.280
and the most important
the answer is to use

00:36:47.280 --> 00:36:48.530
Google Cloud Messaging.

00:36:48.530 --> 00:36:50.840
Like, seriously, use Google
Cloud Messaging.

00:36:50.840 --> 00:36:53.560
It is going to solve most
of these problems.

00:36:53.560 --> 00:36:55.080
It's something which
TripIt, as far as I

00:36:55.080 --> 00:36:56.070
can tell, has done.

00:36:56.070 --> 00:36:58.740
Because there is that option to
choose manual slash push.

00:36:58.740 --> 00:37:01.140
And I had a look in their
manifest, and they are using

00:37:01.140 --> 00:37:01.700
those things.

00:37:01.700 --> 00:37:03.550
But they still have the
options for those more

00:37:03.550 --> 00:37:04.410
frequent updates.

00:37:04.410 --> 00:37:08.200
So I want to hear from the guys
at TripIt and find out,

00:37:08.200 --> 00:37:09.510
are you using it exclusively?

00:37:09.510 --> 00:37:10.970
If not, why not?

00:37:10.970 --> 00:37:13.390
And is there a reason for still
having that option to do

00:37:13.390 --> 00:37:15.120
the manual polling, which
is just going

00:37:15.120 --> 00:37:16.270
to drain the battery.

00:37:16.270 --> 00:37:18.560
IAN NI-LEWIS: Well, there was
a time when Google Cloud

00:37:18.560 --> 00:37:26.440
Messaging was C2DM, and
there was a cap.

00:37:26.440 --> 00:37:28.050
You could only send so
many messages a day.

00:37:28.050 --> 00:37:29.690
Now, that's not in
place anymore.

00:37:29.690 --> 00:37:30.240
RETO MEIER: That's true.

00:37:30.240 --> 00:37:32.800
IAN NI-LEWIS: So it may be
that in the past it was

00:37:32.800 --> 00:37:34.850
difficult for them to guarantee
that they wouldn't

00:37:34.850 --> 00:37:35.790
hit their C2DM limit.

00:37:35.790 --> 00:37:37.060
RETO MEIER: That could
well be the case.

00:37:37.060 --> 00:37:40.020
IAN NI-LEWIS: Now, of course,
Google Cloud Messaging isn't

00:37:40.020 --> 00:37:40.930
doing anything magical.

00:37:40.930 --> 00:37:43.200
It's just taking advantage of
the fact that a lot of apps

00:37:43.200 --> 00:37:44.400
want to do this sort of thing.

00:37:44.400 --> 00:37:48.090
So it makes a lot more sense to
coalesce that into one ping

00:37:48.090 --> 00:37:51.950
that's done intelligently with
battery life in mind rather

00:37:51.950 --> 00:37:55.360
than having everyone ping their
servers at whatever time

00:37:55.360 --> 00:37:56.020
they feel like.

00:37:56.020 --> 00:37:56.490
RETO MEIER: Exactly.

00:37:56.490 --> 00:37:58.550
So it's a way that you can send
a message to a particular

00:37:58.550 --> 00:38:02.290
device or set of devices used
by a particular user,

00:38:02.290 --> 00:38:04.760
informing the app running on
that device that there's

00:38:04.760 --> 00:38:06.390
updates which they
need to retrieve.

00:38:06.390 --> 00:38:08.980
So the result is near-instant
updates with none of the

00:38:08.980 --> 00:38:09.620
battery drain.

00:38:09.620 --> 00:38:12.410
Or at least your app doesn't
get blamed for any of the

00:38:12.410 --> 00:38:15.050
battery drain caused by--

00:38:15.050 --> 00:38:16.790
which you would normally get
with regular poling.

00:38:16.790 --> 00:38:20.110
So you get to blame it all on
Google, which is much cooler.

00:38:20.110 --> 00:38:21.920
If anyone's going to get blamed
for battery drain, it

00:38:21.920 --> 00:38:23.330
may as well be the system
rather than

00:38:23.330 --> 00:38:24.960
your app, if you can.

00:38:24.960 --> 00:38:27.010
So that's kind of
a no-brainer.

00:38:27.010 --> 00:38:28.570
Similarly, you'll want
to pre-fetch as

00:38:28.570 --> 00:38:29.890
much data as possible.

00:38:29.890 --> 00:38:31.220
And it's particularly important

00:38:31.220 --> 00:38:31.990
for an app like TripIt.

00:38:31.990 --> 00:38:34.530
And it's something that they do
really well, in that I had

00:38:34.530 --> 00:38:36.370
to think about whether or not
they did, which made me

00:38:36.370 --> 00:38:37.310
realize that they must.

00:38:37.310 --> 00:38:38.122
Because otherwise, I
would have thrown

00:38:38.122 --> 00:38:39.425
it through a window.

00:38:39.425 --> 00:38:41.440
IAN NI-LEWIS: Right.

00:38:41.440 --> 00:38:43.460
RETO MEIER: Offline access
here is absolutely vital.

00:38:43.460 --> 00:38:45.970
For a lot of travel,
particularly when we were

00:38:45.970 --> 00:38:48.480
jumping from country to country,
you don't have the

00:38:48.480 --> 00:38:51.590
opportunity to buy a local SIM
just for the data, which you

00:38:51.590 --> 00:38:53.410
often do if you're going to
be there for a week or so.

00:38:53.410 --> 00:38:55.860
If you're going to spend 12
hours, you're just going to

00:38:55.860 --> 00:38:58.230
have your core global roaming
SIM, and you're going to

00:38:58.230 --> 00:38:59.970
disable data a lot.

00:38:59.970 --> 00:39:00.560
Airports--

00:39:00.560 --> 00:39:02.700
it often takes a long time once
you get out of flight

00:39:02.700 --> 00:39:04.890
mode for the data connection
to start back up.

00:39:04.890 --> 00:39:07.740
And I want to know where to
tell the taxi driver to go

00:39:07.740 --> 00:39:11.730
without having to wait half an
hour for my phone to turn on

00:39:11.730 --> 00:39:16.010
or to find Wi-Fi in order to be
able to get those updates.

00:39:16.010 --> 00:39:18.300
So for apps like Foursquare,
though,

00:39:18.300 --> 00:39:19.840
pre-fetching can be tricky.

00:39:19.840 --> 00:39:23.280
Because there's no knowing which
places a user is going

00:39:23.280 --> 00:39:25.560
to want to check into, or what
areas, what categories they're

00:39:25.560 --> 00:39:26.400
going to want to explore.

00:39:26.400 --> 00:39:29.120
And you can't pre-fetch
everything because that would

00:39:29.120 --> 00:39:32.480
just be a huge battery drain
and a huge bandwidth drain,

00:39:32.480 --> 00:39:34.010
particularly if you're
roaming.

00:39:34.010 --> 00:39:36.490
So pre-fetching can be kind of
a cat and mouse game between

00:39:36.490 --> 00:39:39.390
trying to get the right details
without wasting too

00:39:39.390 --> 00:39:40.770
much bandwidth.

00:39:40.770 --> 00:39:43.490
So for apps like TripIt, where
the information users want is

00:39:43.490 --> 00:39:46.230
relatively small,
well-encapsulated around a

00:39:46.230 --> 00:39:48.886
trip, and entirely
predictable--

00:39:48.886 --> 00:39:50.570
you even know when they're
going traveling.

00:39:50.570 --> 00:39:52.540
So you can wait to do the
pre-fetching until the day

00:39:52.540 --> 00:39:55.320
before, pull it all down, stick
it on the device, and

00:39:55.320 --> 00:39:56.740
then it's just there, and
it's just working.

00:39:56.740 --> 00:39:58.770
So you can go into offline
airplane mode, and it all

00:39:58.770 --> 00:40:00.980
still works.

00:40:00.980 --> 00:40:03.320
So in that instance, I think
pre-fetching can be really,

00:40:03.320 --> 00:40:05.230
really powerful.

00:40:05.230 --> 00:40:08.060
On the same lines, it's really
important that you limit

00:40:08.060 --> 00:40:09.380
bandwidth as much as possible.

00:40:09.380 --> 00:40:12.030
And that means caching results,
particularly images,

00:40:12.030 --> 00:40:14.500
or anything that's likely
to remain static.

00:40:14.500 --> 00:40:17.730
Better still, your server should
specify the lifetime

00:40:17.730 --> 00:40:19.970
and update time stamps
of its responses.

00:40:19.970 --> 00:40:23.712
And that's what you can see in
this piece of code, which I'm

00:40:23.712 --> 00:40:26.150
just going to step back from it
rather than go full screen.

00:40:26.150 --> 00:40:28.590
So in this code snippet, we're
just checking the server

00:40:28.590 --> 00:40:30.960
response headers to see if we
actually need to bother

00:40:30.960 --> 00:40:32.730
downloading the rest
of response body.

00:40:32.730 --> 00:40:35.000
So this is still going to cost
you in terms of hitting the

00:40:35.000 --> 00:40:37.480
server to see whether there's
anything to get.

00:40:37.480 --> 00:40:39.375
But at least you're not then
downloading extra data that

00:40:39.375 --> 00:40:41.780
you already have or that hasn't
changed since the last

00:40:41.780 --> 00:40:42.840
time you pinged the server.

00:40:42.840 --> 00:40:45.530
IAN NI-LEWIS: If it's possible
to look ahead, too, and

00:40:45.530 --> 00:40:48.100
determine how fresh each
piece of data is,

00:40:48.100 --> 00:40:48.880
that's really useful.

00:40:48.880 --> 00:40:53.000
