IAN NI-LEWIS: Well, and
once again, this

00:49:10.090 --> 00:49:12.840
is a confusing dialogue.

00:49:12.840 --> 00:49:14.710
I've just gone out of something
that's beautiful,

00:49:14.710 --> 00:49:17.060
which is the Android home screen
with the very nice

00:49:17.060 --> 00:49:20.410
widget, and now I'm looking
at this thing that--

00:49:20.410 --> 00:49:24.240
it almost looks like, oops,
some pirated app just took

00:49:24.240 --> 00:49:25.275
over my screen.

00:49:25.275 --> 00:49:25.530
RETO MEIER: Exactly.

00:49:25.530 --> 00:49:27.080
And so you want this to
be small as well.

00:49:27.080 --> 00:49:29.070
We've got a whole bunch
of empty space here.

00:49:29.070 --> 00:49:32.230
So if you're not going full
screen, go as small as you can

00:49:32.230 --> 00:49:34.520
and make this-- it is just
a confirmation dialog.

00:49:34.520 --> 00:49:36.490
I've already selected
all this stuff.

00:49:36.490 --> 00:49:39.500
So you almost want to be able to
have a big Send button and

00:49:39.500 --> 00:49:41.740
then maybe an ability to edit
as well if you want to.

00:49:41.740 --> 00:49:42.080
IAN NI-LEWIS: Right.

00:49:42.080 --> 00:49:43.470
You want the Send button
to be big.

00:49:43.470 --> 00:49:46.090
You want the information to be
there, but not editable.

00:49:46.090 --> 00:49:48.780
Then you want to have
a way to go edit it.

00:49:48.780 --> 00:49:52.890
Because by bringing up the edit
boxes as it is now, A,

00:49:52.890 --> 00:49:54.820
you're introducing possible
error, where somebody

00:49:54.820 --> 00:49:57.790
accidentally hits a key that
they didn't intend to.

00:49:57.790 --> 00:50:01.420
And B, you're making it seem
like I have to edit it, like

00:50:01.420 --> 00:50:03.200
that's my job now
is to edit this.

00:50:03.200 --> 00:50:06.740
But no, I'm just trying to tell
Lassie where to dig to

00:50:06.740 --> 00:50:08.035
get me out from underneath
the rubble.

00:50:08.035 --> 00:50:08.810
RETO MEIER: Precisely.

00:50:08.810 --> 00:50:10.670
IAN NI-LEWIS: I don't
need all this.

00:50:10.670 --> 00:50:13.360
RETO MEIER: And again, what
I really like here is this

00:50:13.360 --> 00:50:14.540
ability to set a timer.

00:50:14.540 --> 00:50:17.610
So you can say, set it five
minutes into the future.

00:50:17.610 --> 00:50:18.560
IAN NI-LEWIS: That would be
great if they had used the new

00:50:18.560 --> 00:50:19.590
control for that, though.

00:50:19.590 --> 00:50:20.230
RETO MEIER: It kind of would.

00:50:20.230 --> 00:50:21.970
IAN NI-LEWIS: That's
intensely horrible.

00:50:21.970 --> 00:50:22.270
RETO MEIER: It is.

00:50:22.270 --> 00:50:24.700
And it's a really useful
function, so I would actually

00:50:24.700 --> 00:50:27.480
want to have that as
the main thing.

00:50:27.480 --> 00:50:30.080
So the two main things here are
I want send it now, send

00:50:30.080 --> 00:50:32.870
in a few minutes, and
edit also, maybe.

00:50:32.870 --> 00:50:35.510
So you almost want to flip the
importance of those things, so

00:50:35.510 --> 00:50:38.410
that the editing functionality
is up on the top right, and

00:50:38.410 --> 00:50:40.930
the being able to set a
timer is right there.

00:50:40.930 --> 00:50:43.750
Also note that there's no way to
cancel here as well, which

00:50:43.750 --> 00:50:44.760
is interesting.

00:50:44.760 --> 00:50:46.770
So I'm done, but I
changed my mind.

00:50:46.770 --> 00:50:47.570
Do I just want to send it now?

00:50:47.570 --> 00:50:49.550
I kind of can't, which
is again--

00:50:49.550 --> 00:50:50.850
it's just that user flow.

00:50:50.850 --> 00:50:53.590
You want to make everything as
simple and easy as possible,

00:50:53.590 --> 00:50:55.500
and make it impossible for
a user to do it wrong.

00:50:55.500 --> 00:50:57.190
It's never the right answer
to say, oh, you're

00:50:57.190 --> 00:50:58.940
using the app wrong.

00:50:58.940 --> 00:51:00.500
That should never even
be an option.

00:51:00.500 --> 00:51:02.510
They should only ever be
able to use it right.

00:51:02.510 --> 00:51:04.780
One thing that they have done
nicely here is that one of the

00:51:04.780 --> 00:51:07.566
recipients you can set is, share
with other app, which is

00:51:07.566 --> 00:51:08.340
what we've got ticked now.

00:51:08.340 --> 00:51:12.690
So if we do that, we can see
it's set up an ongoing

00:51:12.690 --> 00:51:15.470
notification, which is--

00:51:15.470 --> 00:51:16.460
time is set to an hour.

00:51:16.460 --> 00:51:17.100
Interesting.

00:51:17.100 --> 00:51:19.080
I'm going to cancel that
one and set off

00:51:19.080 --> 00:51:22.280
another one really quickly.

00:51:22.280 --> 00:51:25.530
Now, what it's going to do is
find my current location.

00:51:25.530 --> 00:51:27.780
So now, all that information
we have it earlier on about

00:51:27.780 --> 00:51:29.720
being able to find a location
really quickly

00:51:29.720 --> 00:51:31.030
becomes really important.

00:51:31.030 --> 00:51:33.650
Because I don't want to sit here
waiting for it to find my

00:51:33.650 --> 00:51:35.050
GPS signal.

00:51:35.050 --> 00:51:36.860
Anything is good enough
right now.

00:51:36.860 --> 00:51:38.760
So you can by all means check
to see whether you can get

00:51:38.760 --> 00:51:39.800
something really accurate.

00:51:39.800 --> 00:51:41.970
If it doesn't happen within
5 seconds, screw it.

00:51:41.970 --> 00:51:43.920
Go with what you had
last and send that.

00:51:43.920 --> 00:51:45.040
Maybe send a second message.

00:51:45.040 --> 00:51:46.410
Maybe make that an option.

00:51:46.410 --> 00:51:49.155
So that's going to keep doing
its thing, retrieving current

00:51:49.155 --> 00:51:51.660
location, for a while.

00:51:51.660 --> 00:51:54.860
Interestingly, the app comes up
when that happens as well.

00:51:54.860 --> 00:51:56.680
So I think you've probably done
something weird with your

00:51:56.680 --> 00:51:58.500
intent receivers there.

00:51:58.500 --> 00:52:00.050
So this shouldn't be getting
triggered from

00:52:00.050 --> 00:52:00.810
clicking on the widget.

00:52:00.810 --> 00:52:02.900
That's not a great
user experience.

00:52:02.900 --> 00:52:04.780
So you want to make sure that
doesn't end up on the activity

00:52:04.780 --> 00:52:07.490
stack associated with your
activity when you're entering

00:52:07.490 --> 00:52:09.540
it from the widget.

00:52:09.540 --> 00:52:12.010
So once that's happened, it
will actually then let you

00:52:12.010 --> 00:52:14.460
send that message via any of the
other apps that you've got

00:52:14.460 --> 00:52:18.640
on the system, which is a nice
way of doing things.

00:52:18.640 --> 00:52:21.440
And in fact, I guess, maybe take
that as an opportunity to

00:52:21.440 --> 00:52:23.010
talk a little bit about
exactly what

00:52:23.010 --> 00:52:26.110
they're doing there.

00:52:26.110 --> 00:52:28.620
Oh, there it is.

00:52:28.620 --> 00:52:29.710
It's now got the location.

00:52:29.710 --> 00:52:32.010
And we can share it using any of
the apps which are capable

00:52:32.010 --> 00:52:33.790
of sharing text,
which is nice.

00:52:39.650 --> 00:52:41.940
As we were saying, perhaps even
more so than Foursquare,

00:52:41.940 --> 00:52:44.560
low-latency location detection
is absolutely

00:52:44.560 --> 00:52:46.090
critical for this app.

00:52:46.090 --> 00:52:47.740
So I'd be interested to know
from the developers what

00:52:47.740 --> 00:52:49.940
techniques they're using to get
that quick and accurate

00:52:49.940 --> 00:52:52.920
location fix, particularly
because it's not that quick.

00:52:52.920 --> 00:52:55.320
So I'd like to see them doing
some work to improve that.

00:52:55.320 --> 00:52:58.810
But one of the things they have
done well is this sharing

00:52:58.810 --> 00:53:01.420
using any app dialog, which I
really like, and which is

00:53:01.420 --> 00:53:04.000
something that TripIt has done
pretty well as well, making

00:53:04.000 --> 00:53:08.060
use of intents to add more
functionality to their apps

00:53:08.060 --> 00:53:10.230
without having to do
any extra work.

00:53:10.230 --> 00:53:11.010
IAN NI-LEWIS: We're running
out of time.

00:53:11.010 --> 00:53:14.060
But let's quickly go over what
you'd need to do to add the

00:53:14.060 --> 00:53:15.500
sort of share intent
to your app.

00:53:15.500 --> 00:53:17.360
RETO MEIER: Absolutely.

00:53:17.360 --> 00:53:19.630
Let's see.

00:53:19.630 --> 00:53:22.352
So the details for what I'm
describing here are all on

00:53:22.352 --> 00:53:24.700
this Android training class
on sharing content.

00:53:24.700 --> 00:53:27.520
But the basics are actually
pretty straightforward.

00:53:27.520 --> 00:53:28.680
You can create--

00:53:28.680 --> 00:53:30.170
IAN NI-LEWIS: You know, all that
typography looked right

00:53:30.170 --> 00:53:30.960
on my laptop.

00:53:30.960 --> 00:53:32.250
RETO MEIER: That's
they all say.

00:53:32.250 --> 00:53:32.760
IAN NI-LEWIS: Yes, I know.

00:53:32.760 --> 00:53:34.820
RETO MEIER: It was fine
on my machine.

00:53:34.820 --> 00:53:36.410
So you create a new intent.

00:53:36.410 --> 00:53:39.760
You set the action to send and
then populate the text extra

00:53:39.760 --> 00:53:41.490
with the text you want
to transmit.

00:53:41.490 --> 00:53:43.870
Then you just start an activity
using that intent.

00:53:43.870 --> 00:53:47.940
Now, in this example here, I'm
actually forcing the activity

00:53:47.940 --> 00:53:50.170
chooser to be displayed
every time.

00:53:50.170 --> 00:53:53.800
That's because users will often
choose a default app for

00:53:53.800 --> 00:53:55.410
handling a lot of content.

00:53:55.410 --> 00:53:58.930
And for an app like this, you
actually want to give the user

00:53:58.930 --> 00:54:01.650
a chance to say, well, which
specific thing do you want?

00:54:01.650 --> 00:54:04.110
Because you've actually ticked
a box to say, send using

00:54:04.110 --> 00:54:04.590
another app.

00:54:04.590 --> 00:54:07.080
It kind of makes sense to give
them an opportunity to say

00:54:07.080 --> 00:54:10.250
which app that they want.

00:54:10.250 --> 00:54:12.880
So given that we are just about
out of time, I think

00:54:12.880 --> 00:54:15.840
happily, we're just onto the
prescriptions for each of the

00:54:15.840 --> 00:54:17.040
apps that we want to look at.

00:54:17.040 --> 00:54:19.890
So let me pop all of this behind
us, and we'll bring

00:54:19.890 --> 00:54:21.290
each of these up.

00:54:21.290 --> 00:54:22.610
So I think this is the--

00:54:22.610 --> 00:54:24.660
these are the prescriptions
for Foursquare.

00:54:24.660 --> 00:54:25.760
IAN NI-LEWIS: Indeed.

00:54:25.760 --> 00:54:27.100
RETO MEIER: We didn't have a
lot because they've done a

00:54:27.100 --> 00:54:27.880
pretty good job.

00:54:27.880 --> 00:54:29.320
IAN NI-LEWIS: No, they
really have, yeah.

00:54:29.320 --> 00:54:30.000
RETO MEIER: I'm pretty
impressed.

00:54:30.000 --> 00:54:33.780
I mean, the Foursquare team have
spent a lot time really

00:54:33.780 --> 00:54:35.800
refining and honing their
app to try and make

00:54:35.800 --> 00:54:36.730
it as good as possible.

00:54:36.730 --> 00:54:38.620
They're really passionate about
creating a pure Android

00:54:38.620 --> 00:54:41.780
experience, something that is
really user friendly, that

00:54:41.780 --> 00:54:44.633
makes the phone work better,
that is always a positive and

00:54:44.633 --> 00:54:46.290
not a negative, so
hats off to them.

00:54:46.290 --> 00:54:46.740
IAN NI-LEWIS: Indeed.

00:54:46.740 --> 00:54:49.750
But as with any app that was
designed almost exclusively in

00:54:49.750 --> 00:54:53.050
the Bay Area, it simply assumes
too much about your

00:54:53.050 --> 00:54:53.740
network connection.

00:54:53.740 --> 00:54:57.760
It needs to be better offline
and also better during

00:54:57.760 --> 00:54:58.810
changing network conditions.

00:54:58.810 --> 00:55:00.870
RETO MEIER: And so for me, I
guess the key thing-- and I

00:55:00.870 --> 00:55:02.440
have brought this up with
the Foursquare team.

00:55:02.440 --> 00:55:05.230
And I know they have good
reasons for not doing this,

00:55:05.230 --> 00:55:07.100
but I'm going to mention it
anyway for anyone else who's

00:55:07.100 --> 00:55:10.030
doing an app which does
something similar, is support

00:55:10.030 --> 00:55:12.420
for being able to check
in when I'm offline.

00:55:12.420 --> 00:55:16.010
So in the Bay Area, going inside
ends up having better

00:55:16.010 --> 00:55:18.550
network access because everyone
has free Wi-Fi.

00:55:18.550 --> 00:55:22.270
Not the case in London, and A
lot of the good venues are all

00:55:22.270 --> 00:55:25.400
three stories underground so
that they don't get bombed in

00:55:25.400 --> 00:55:28.090
the Second World War, but it
also means they have really

00:55:28.090 --> 00:55:31.240
bad network coverage and no free
Wi-Fi, because nothing is

00:55:31.240 --> 00:55:32.560
free in London.

00:55:32.560 --> 00:55:35.570
So being able to check in, and
then just have all of that get

00:55:35.570 --> 00:55:37.980
cached in a queue that then will
check me into all these

00:55:37.980 --> 00:55:40.055
places once I do get network
access would be

00:55:40.055 --> 00:55:41.870
a really nice feature.

00:55:41.870 --> 00:55:43.230
So I'm going to take this
opportunity to ask the

00:55:43.230 --> 00:55:44.300
Foursquare guys to do that.

00:55:44.300 --> 00:55:44.640
IAN NI-LEWIS: I would
love that.

00:55:44.640 --> 00:55:45.660
RETO MEIER: Again.

00:55:45.660 --> 00:55:47.040
TripIt--

00:55:47.040 --> 00:55:49.870
we had a couple more suggestions
for them.

00:55:49.870 --> 00:55:52.010
Again, this is an app
that we really love.

00:55:52.010 --> 00:55:54.450
And this is one of those apps
which does everything right in

00:55:54.450 --> 00:55:56.390
terms of the service
that it provides.

00:55:56.390 --> 00:55:59.290
Absolutely love it, totally
indispensable, would use it

00:55:59.290 --> 00:56:01.760
even if it was a terminal
prompt.

00:56:01.760 --> 00:56:04.280
So that means that a lot of
what we're actually saying

00:56:04.280 --> 00:56:06.050
here is-- in a way,
it's nit picky.

00:56:06.050 --> 00:56:08.270
But it's also something which
can make the app that much

00:56:08.270 --> 00:56:10.120
more appealing, that much
more fun to use.

00:56:10.120 --> 00:56:12.960
And I think the key thing here
is it would be great to see

00:56:12.960 --> 00:56:15.450
them take another pass at the
design, another pass at the

00:56:15.450 --> 00:56:19.530
UI, now that we've had these
changes to Holo, so kind of a

00:56:19.530 --> 00:56:23.430
UI overhaul would be kind
of nice to see.

00:56:23.430 --> 00:56:25.710
So we've got all the
details there--

00:56:25.710 --> 00:56:29.560
things like getting rid of the
menu button; not having to

00:56:29.560 --> 00:56:32.450
click to load more lists, just
having that automatically fill

00:56:32.450 --> 00:56:35.630
as we scroll; more use of
C2DM; better copying and

00:56:35.630 --> 00:56:38.150
pasting; and overall
cleaner navigation.

00:56:38.150 --> 00:56:42.440
And our third contender, the
Share Where location widget.

00:56:42.440 --> 00:56:45.530
Again, I think the key here is
really a simplified workflow.

00:56:45.530 --> 00:56:47.840
Everything should be easier,
particularly the first time.

00:56:47.840 --> 00:56:50.230
It should just be click,
click, that's my wife's

00:56:50.230 --> 00:56:52.200
contact, done.

00:56:52.200 --> 00:56:54.360
IAN NI-LEWIS: We have talked
about this many times, that a

00:56:54.360 --> 00:56:57.190
lot of apps are just difficult
to get into.

00:56:57.190 --> 00:56:59.370
And what you need do is just
figure out what the most

00:56:59.370 --> 00:57:01.270
common use case is,
and Just fill that

00:57:01.270 --> 00:57:02.710
stuff in for the user.

00:57:02.710 --> 00:57:03.640
RETO MEIER: Exactly.

00:57:03.640 --> 00:57:05.440
It seems kind of
counterintuitive in a lot of

00:57:05.440 --> 00:57:08.400
ways to say, we want you to
remove some of the options

00:57:08.400 --> 00:57:09.410
from your app.

00:57:09.410 --> 00:57:11.390
But it kind of works,
particularly for something

00:57:11.390 --> 00:57:14.360
like this, which is really
focused, is figure out what is

00:57:14.360 --> 00:57:16.150
it that people are downloading
this app to do.

00:57:16.150 --> 00:57:18.730
And you can use analytics for
that to find out what are the

00:57:18.730 --> 00:57:20.280
most common settings that
they're choosing?

00:57:20.280 --> 00:57:22.610
What are the most common options
that they're clicking?

00:57:22.610 --> 00:57:25.340
And make that not only the
default, but maybe the only

00:57:25.340 --> 00:57:26.320
thing that you can do.

00:57:26.320 --> 00:57:29.040
And then worry about expanding
those features in a way that's

00:57:29.040 --> 00:57:31.180
consistent with the app usage
and easier to use

00:57:31.180 --> 00:57:31.940
as time goes on.

00:57:31.940 --> 00:57:33.840
IAN NI-LEWIS: And definitely
ditch the gingerbread.

00:57:33.840 --> 00:57:34.460
We're sorry.

00:57:34.460 --> 00:57:36.160
We're sorry we ever
put it out.

00:57:36.160 --> 00:57:36.740
Go to Holo.

00:57:36.740 --> 00:57:37.370
RETO MEIER: It happens.

00:57:37.370 --> 00:57:40.110
But yeah, make a UI that's
consistent with the rest of

00:57:40.110 --> 00:57:42.540
the framework, preferably
something that's Holo, but

00:57:42.540 --> 00:57:44.240
definitely something which
doesn't feel like it's been

00:57:44.240 --> 00:57:46.520
yanked out of an earlier
phone and stuck in the

00:57:46.520 --> 00:57:47.230
middle of your app.

00:57:47.230 --> 00:57:49.090
And that's, again, particularly
important for

00:57:49.090 --> 00:57:50.730
anything which is
widget-based.

00:57:50.730 --> 00:57:53.230
Because users aren't going
to be in your app much.

00:57:53.230 --> 00:57:56.460
But when they are, you don't
want to make it feel jarring.

00:57:56.460 --> 00:57:58.430
So that's kind of an
important step.

00:57:58.430 --> 00:58:00.710
And also the widget, the widget
is what you're doing.

00:58:00.710 --> 00:58:02.230
So make sure the widgets
are really beautiful.

00:58:02.230 --> 00:58:07.580
They look kind of jaggy and
blurred on the Galaxy Nexus.

00:58:07.580 --> 00:58:10.440
So make sure you've got the
right assets, nice scalable

00:58:10.440 --> 00:58:12.490
assets, so that everything
looks really beautiful.

00:58:12.490 --> 00:58:13.870
Because if it's going to live
on the home screen, it needs

00:58:13.870 --> 00:58:14.590
to look nice.

00:58:14.590 --> 00:58:17.370
People want their home
screens to look nice.

00:58:17.370 --> 00:58:23.650
So I think that just about takes
us to the end of today's

00:58:23.650 --> 00:58:28.140
"App Clinic." So two, both
Foursquare and TripIt of the

00:58:28.140 --> 00:58:29.940
apps that we looked at, are
already featured in Google

00:58:29.940 --> 00:58:32.020
Play's Editor's Choice category,
which makes them a

00:58:32.020 --> 00:58:33.990
good chance to join the pure
Android collection,

00:58:33.990 --> 00:58:36.920
particularly Foursquare, which,
having looked at again

00:58:36.920 --> 00:58:39.050
today, just continues
to impress.

00:58:39.050 --> 00:58:41.460
So wherever possible in the
future, we're going to

00:58:41.460 --> 00:58:43.370
prioritize reviewing
apps by people who

00:58:43.370 --> 00:58:45.400
self-nominated them.

00:58:45.400 --> 00:58:48.970
So to be sure, please be sure
to head over to Trello to

00:58:48.970 --> 00:58:50.000
nominate your apps.

00:58:50.000 --> 00:58:53.100
And in fact I'll stick that
in the background as well.

